Description: A lesson about the difference of how to distinguish what is science versus non-science.  The six criteria are explained as to what makes science distinguishable: consistent, observable, natural, predictable, testable, and tentative.  Each criteria is provided with a discussion to have with students.

Resource Name: Scientific Explanations and Interpretations Video Lecture
Description: Video lecture on the difference between fact and opinion.

Resource Name: Power Point Presentations About the Scientific Method
Description: Free power point presentation for teachers to use for the classroom about the scientific method.  The concept is broken down and there are activities to do whilst teaching the scientific method.
Video explaining what science is

Resource Name: Papering The Skies With The Scientific Method
Description: A lesson plan that uses the scientific method to study paper airplanes.

Video lecture on why we use science to understand our natural world and the process of the scientific method to come to a conclusion.

A geoscientist stresses the importance of learning earth science. He also explains the changes on our planet through geological time. It is a six-minute video and contains nice photographs and good narration.

Resource Name: About Telescopes - the apparent size of things
Description: A video lecture on how a telescope works to see objects clearer.

Resource Name: Video lecture on divergent plate boundaries in the ocean
Description: Video lecture on divergent plate boundaries in the ocean. Includes information about the mid-ocean ridge, sea-floor spreading, and evidence of sea-floor spreading.

Animated video of weathering, erosion, physical and chemical weathering, how they work together to break down rocks.
Video on how clouds form
Video on how tornadoes form, how to monitor tornadoes, and how to stay safe.

Resource Name: How a Hurricane is Born - The Science of Hurricanes
Description: Short video on how a hurricane can be made.

Resource Name: Food Web Slide Show and Vocabulary
Description: Slide show with vocabulary words include: ecosystem, food chain, food web, producer, autotroph, consumer, heterotroph, herbivore, primary consumer, carnivore, secondary consumer, omnivore, decomposer, scavenger, detrivore, predator, and trophic level.

Resource Name: TED Ed - Deep Ocean Mysteries and Wonders
Description: In the deepest, darkest parts of the oceans are ecosystems with more diversity than a tropical rainforest. Taking us on a voyage into the ocean -- from the deepest trenches to the remains of the Titanic -- marine biologist David Gallo explores the wonder and beauty of marine life.
How can a "thumbs up" sign help us remember five processes that impact evolution? The story of the Five Fingers of Evolution gives us a clever way of understanding change in gene pools over time.

Paul Andersen details the evolutionary processes of speciation and extinction. Stickleback evolution in Lake Loberg is used as example of rapid speciation. Adaptive radiation is illustrated using the Hawaiian honeycreeper. A brief discussion of extinctions and mass extinctions is also included.
